ing to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bassett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>basset</i> ‘of low stature’, a diminutive of <i>basse</i> ‘low, short’, either a nickname for a short person or a status name for someone of humble origins.","Altered form of French   Bessette   1 or <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2).","History: William Bassett (<i>c.</i> 1598–1667) came to Plymouth, MA, from Kent, England, in the 1620s; <i>c.</i> 1650 he moved to Duxbury and subesequently to Bridgewater. He had many prominent descendants, among them one of the earliest families on Martha's Vineyard. — The surname <i>Bassett</i> of French origin (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Armand, Adrien, Normand, Alphonse, Lucien, Cecile, Herve, Jacques, Laurent, Aime.","French: topographic name designating a small wood of birches, from Occitan <i>bès</i> ‘birch tree’ (see   Besse  ), or a habitational name from (La) Bessette, the name of several places in the southern part of France.","Alternatively, an altered form of French <b>Besset</b>: topographic name, a cognate of 1 above. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":5,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":25,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":35,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":45,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecily de Bassett was born in 1061, in Leicestershire, England, her father, Thurstane de Bassett, was 31 and her mother, Nancy de Bassett, was 16. She married Robert de Roelent in 1085, in Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She die